content.text:
Now I can see the issue more clearly. Let me trace it:

1. On page refresh, `bridgeConnected` initializes to `false` (line 31: `useState(false)`)
2. There's a 30-second polling fallback for bridge status (line 1384-1394)
3. The `bridge:connected` WS event sets it to true (line 1367)
4. On WS disconnect, it sets `bridgeConnected = false` (line 1379)

The problem is: on page refresh, the user-client WS reconnects (useWebSocket auto-reconnects), and the bridge WS is still connected (it's a separate process). But `bridgeConnected` resets to `false` and needs the `bridge:connected` event to set it back. The polling fallback runs every 30s.

But the user says "every time i refresh the page the bridge is discconnected" — so even after waiting, it stays disconnected. This means the bridge might actually be disconnecting. 

Let me investigate why. The bridge WebSocket is separate — it shouldn't be affected by browser refresh. But maybe there's something on the server side that disconnects the bridge when the user client disconnects? Let me look at the `ws.on('close')` handler in `handleUserClientUpgrade` more carefully.

Actually, looking at line 461:
```
ws.on('close', () => {
    if (currentAbortController) {
      currentAbortController.abort(new Error('cancelled_by_disconnect'));
      currentAbortController = null;
    }
    isProcessing = false;
    queuedMessage = null;
  });
```

This just aborts any in-flight request. It doesn't disconnect the bridge.

But wait — at line 1379: `onDisconnect: () => { setBridgeConnected(false); }`. This sets bridgeConnected to false when the user-client WS disconnects. Then the 30s polling should fix it. But maybe the polling isn't working properly, or there's a race condition.

Let me also check: when the user-client WS reconnects after page refresh, does the server push a `bridge:connected` event? Let me check `userClientManager` for how it handles new connections and bridge status.

Actually, let me focus on the more critical issue: the AI response when bridge is disconnected. The user says:
"Hmm, still can't reach those files directly — the file system tools aren't connected in this session. But you know what? I can still help! If you just copy and paste..."

This is the AI trying to use web_search or url_fetch tools (the only tools available when bridge is offline) and then giving up. The system prompt doesn't tell the AI it needs to ask the user to reconnect the bridge.

Now there's already a client-side message: 
```ts
if (effectiveProjectId && !bridgeConnected && looksLikeExecutionTask) {
    addMessage('system', 'Bridge is offline, so SUNy cannot create files or run commands right now. Reconnect the bridge to execute this task end-to-end.');
}
```

But the AI itself doesn't know to say this. Let me look at the system prompt to see if there's a bridge-related instruction.

Let me look at the prompt-registry or where the system prompt is assembled.

